k}$ and $G_{d,k}$ are the affine and the linear\nGrassmannians equipped with their respective Haar measures. The case $p=0$\nreduces to an affine version of the integral formula of Furstenberg and Tzkoni.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 17 Nov 2017 15:02:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 5 Apr 2019 14:52:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-08-08"}
{"id":"1711.06579","submitter":"Dmitry Pelinovsky","authors":"Jinbing Chen and Dmitry E. Pelinovsky","title":"Rogue periodic waves of the focusing NLS equation","comments":"20 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1098/rspa.2017.0814","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.PS math-ph math.DS math.MP nlin.SI","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Rogue waves on the periodic background are considered for the nonlinear\nSchrodinger (NLS) equation in the focusing case. The two periodic wave\nsolutions are expressed by the Jacobian elliptic functions dn and cn. Both\nperiodic waves are modulationally unstable with respect to long-wave\nperturbations. Exact solutions for the rogue waves on the periodic background\nare constructed by using the explicit expressions for the periodic\neigenfunctions of the Zakharov-Shabat spectral problem and the Darboux\ntransformations. These exact solutions labeled as rogue periodic waves\ngeneralize the classical rogue wave (the so-called Peregrine's breather). The\nmagnification factor of the rogue periodic waves is computed as a function of\nthe wave amplitude (the elliptic modulus). Rogue periodic waves constructed\nhere are compared with the rogue wave patterns obtained numerically in recent\npublications.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 17 Nov 2017 15:05:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-04-04"}
